Lab 11 - Insecure Direct Object References (Static File Access)
Objective
Exploit an Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR) vulnerability to retrieve Carlos's password from a chat transcript and log in as Carlos.

Background
The application provides a live chat feature.

When a chat session ends, the transcript is saved directly on the server's file system and made available for download.

Instead of using secure authorization checks, the application retrieves transcripts using predictable static filenames.

Vulnerability
Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR) – Static File Access

The application exposed chat transcripts using sequential filenames such as:

/download-transcript/1.txt
The server did not verify whether the authenticated user owned the requested transcript.

Initial Observation
Started a live chat session.

After ending the conversation, selected:

View transcript
Burp Suite captured a request similar to:

GET /download-transcript/5.txt
The transcript was downloaded as a plain text file.

Methodology
Step 1 – Capture Transcript Request
Observed the request:

GET /download-transcript/5.txt
The filename appeared predictable.

Step 2 – Test File Enumeration
Modified the filename in Burp Repeater:

5.txt
↓

4.txt
3.txt
2.txt
1.txt
Existing files returned:

HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Non-existent files returned:

HTTP/1.1 404 Not Found
This confirmed that transcript filenames were sequential and accessible.

Step 3 – Inspect Other Users' Transcripts
Reviewed the contents of the accessible transcript files.

Transcript 1.txt contained a conversation involving Carlos.

The conversation revealed Carlos's password.

Step 4 – Authenticate as Carlos
Logged into the application using:

Username: carlos
Password: Retrieved from 1.txt
The lab was successfully solved.

Why the Attack Worked
The application directly trusted the filename supplied in the request.

It only verified whether the requested file existed.

It never verified whether the authenticated user was authorized to access that transcript.

