Root Cause
The application used predictable object references (filenames) without enforcing authorization.

Authorization should be based on resource ownership, not merely file existence.

Impact
Successful exploitation may expose:

Customer support conversations
Passwords
Personal information
Internal discussions
API keys
Financial information
Medical records
If sensitive information is disclosed, attackers may gain unauthorized access to user accounts.

Prevention
Verify ownership before serving any file.
Avoid predictable sequential filenames.
Use random, unguessable identifiers where appropriate.
Store metadata linking each file to its owner.
Perform server-side authorization checks for every file request.
